On Fri, Mar 20, 2009 at 11:28 AM, Eric J. Bowman &lt;eric@...&gt;wrote:

&gt; There&#39;s nothing to be done about caches serving stale data, not with
&gt; cache control headers anyway. But there is the special case of DELETE,
&gt; which allows immediate cache expiration on those specific caches between
&gt; the user requesting the DELETE and the origin server. Deleting members
&gt; 2, 5 and 9 from a collection in any way other than three separate DELETE
&gt; operations eliminates even the *possibility* of prompt expiration of 2,
&gt; 5 and 9 from those specific caches pertinent to the user who requested
&gt; the DELETE (other users have no compelling need for immediate
&gt; expiration). You&#39;ve gone from 99% probability that deleted resources
&gt; will be expired from the cache of the user who requested the delete, to
&gt; 0%.
&gt;

An off-the-wall suggestion: Since DELETE is idempotent, how about sending
the separate DELETE commands to the server after the batch delete anyway,
for the sheer purpose of invalidating the intermediate caches?

--001636c5b1c70a891b04658c0058
